Transparent Bias News Engine (TBNE) v0.1

PantheonOS / Money Bin / Truth Infrastructure

Purpose

Build a news system that does not pretend to be bias-free.
Instead, it makes bias:
	•	explicit
	•	adjustable
	•	inspectable
	•	testable against evidence

The goal is not to produce one final “correct” narrative. The goal is to separate:
	•	what is known
	•	what is inferred
	•	what is weighted
	•	what is uncertain

Then let users compare frames without hiding the machinery.

⸻

1. Core Thesis

Bias cannot be eliminated, but it can be declared, parameterized, and audited.

Traditional news hides weighting inside:
	•	editorial choices
	•	headline wording
	•	omission
	•	framing
	•	order of presentation

TBNE moves those hidden choices into visible system components.

⸻

2. System Goals

Functional goals
	•	Aggregate news from diverse sources
	•	Extract claims, facts, quotes, and uncertainties
	•	Distinguish source evidence from interpretation
	•	Generate multiple summaries from the same fact base
	•	Show how different weighting profiles change narrative output
	•	Expose contradictions, missing data, and confidence levels

Normative goals
	•	Increase epistemic transparency
	•	Reduce hidden persuasion
	•	Improve user agency
	•	Make disagreement legible
	•	Align interpretation closer to evidence

Non-goals
	•	Perfect objectivity
	•	Replacing all journalism
	•	Telling users what to believe
	•	Enforcing one ideology
	•	Collapsing uncertainty into false certainty

⸻

3. Core Principles

3.1 Facts first

Narratives are downstream of evidence.

3.2 Weightings must be visible

Every summary should be reproducible from declared settings.

3.3 Uncertainty is first-class

Unknowns and disputes must be shown, not smoothed over.

3.4 Source provenance is mandatory

Every major claim must trace back to a source.

3.5 Compare frames, do not hide them

Differences between interpretations are part of the product.

3.6 Bias is safer when declared

Hidden bias is more dangerous than visible bias.

