5. System Architecture

Layer 1: Source Intake

Collect data from:
	•	major news outlets
	•	international outlets
	•	official statements
	•	court filings
	•	press releases
	•	transcripts
	•	public datasets
	•	direct video/audio where possible

Output

Raw source objects with metadata.

Example:

{
  "source_id": "src_001",
  "title": "Central Bank Raises Rates",
  "publisher": "Example News",
  "published_at": "2026-04-10T12:00:00Z",
  "url": "https://example.com/article",
  "source_type": "news_article",
  "raw_text": "...",
  "author": "Jane Doe"
}


⸻

Layer 2: Claim Extraction

Extract:
	•	factual claims
	•	numerical claims
	•	quoted statements
	•	causal claims
	•	predictions
	•	uncertainty markers

Output

Claim objects linked to evidence spans.

Example:

{
  "claim_id": "clm_014",
  "text": "The central bank raised its benchmark rate by 0.25 percentage points.",
  "claim_type": "factual",
  "source_id": "src_001",
  "evidence_span": "paragraph_3",
  "entities": ["central bank", "benchmark rate"],
  "time_reference": "2026-04-10",
  "confidence": 0.93
}


⸻

Layer 3: Fact Graph Construction

Merge compatible claims into canonical event graph nodes.

Purposes
	•	deduplicate repeated facts
	•	cluster contradictions
	•	preserve source diversity
	•	build event timeline

Output

Event graph with:
	•	confirmed facts
	•	contested claims
	•	missing data
	•	temporal sequence

⸻

Layer 4: Bias Profiles

Bias is represented as an explicit weighting object.

A bias profile does not invent facts. It changes:
	•	salience
	•	ordering
	•	emphasis
	•	preferred metrics
	•	cost functions

Example profiles:
	•	Neutral baseline
	•	Economic-heavy
	•	Human-impact-heavy
	•	Institutional-trust-heavy
	•	Civil-liberties-heavy
	•	National-security-heavy
	•	User-custom

Example:

{
  "profile_id": "economic_heavy_v1",
  "name": "Economic Heavy",
  "weights": {
    "economic_impact": 0.40,
    "human_impact": 0.15,
    "institutional_stability": 0.20,
    "civil_liberties": 0.10,
    "geopolitical_risk": 0.10,
    "novelty_penalty": 0.05
  },
  "language_rules": {
    "emotional_language_penalty": 0.8,
    "speculation_penalty": 0.7,
    "headline_sensationalism_penalty": 0.9
  }
}


⸻

Layer 5: Narrative Generation

Generate summaries from the same fact graph under different bias profiles.

Required output sections
	•	Confirmed facts
	•	Most relevant uncertainties
	•	Key interpretations under current weighting
	•	What this frame prioritizes
	•	What this frame may underweight

Example summary structure:

{
  "summary_id": "sum_100",
  "event_id": "evt_22",
  "profile_id": "human_impact_v1",
  "confirmed_facts": [
    "Rates were raised by 0.25 percentage points."
  ],
  "uncertainties": [
    "Long-term inflation effects remain disputed."
  ],
  "narrative_summary": "This decision may increase household borrowing costs...",
  "weighting_explanation": "This frame prioritizes household impact over market interpretation."
}


⸻

Layer 6: Comparative View

This is one of the most important features.

For any event, show:
	•	shared facts across all frames
	•	claims with disagreement
	•	emphasis differences
	•	omitted consequences by frame
	•	confidence deltas

Example user view

Event: Central bank rate hike

Shared facts
	•	Rate increased by 0.25
	•	Vote passed 7-2
	•	Effective date is next week

Economic-heavy frame
	•	Focuses on inflation and markets

Human-impact frame
	•	Focuses on debt burden and household cost

Civil-liberties frame
	•	Minimal relevance, low weighting

